{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee3c8295-123c-4ba8-adb0-52fc702cb740","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile:\n\n```bash\n# 1. Install the tool inside the container\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your app's PID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a 30-second CPU trace\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- Use `--format speedscope` if you want a portable flame graph without Windows tools.\n- `kubectl cp <pod>:<path>/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace` to copy the file out.\n- If you can't install tools in the container, use a **sidecar** with the SDK or consider `dotnet-monitor` for always-on diagnostics.\n- For very high CPU, `perf` (Linux native) can capture both managed and native frames when combined with `crossgen2`/`perfmap` support, but `dotnet-trace` is simpler for most cases.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5f561c3c-dc4c-47a5-a4e0-adcc790b284c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question - I can answer from knowledge without needing tools.","outputTokens":354,"requestId":"9428:262085:183B763:1B879F1:69E81E51"},"id":"37d065a4-aacd-4b8e-a1bb-afde9a99b824","timestamp":"2026-04-22T01:03:22.806Z","parentId":"4c3c4b06-fbbf-480c-98a8-34f181fdf3f9"}
